gomodel:SYNGO_1612  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Automated change 2024-03-14: GO:0030285 replaced by GO:0030672" , "Rationale: Osborne et al perform subcellular fractionation of rat brains and show co-distribution of syt-1 and syt-2 in fractions eluted from a size-exclusion column that are highly enriched in synaptic vesicles (Fig. 1). The presence of syt-1 and syt-2 in these fractions is monitored by immunoblotting using isoform specific antibodies (antigenic sequences in the N-terminal, where sequence similarity between syt-1 and syt-2 is low). The authors suggest that both syts are localized to the same population of SVs and verify their observation by immunoisolation SVs with anti-syt-1 IgGs and WB for SV marker protein synaptobrevin-2 and syt-2. Additionally, Osborne et al solubilize proteins from crude SV fractions from rat cortex and cerebellum with octylglucoside and perform immunoprecipitation with anti-syt-1 antibodies and observe specific enrichment of syt-2 in the IP sample in contrast to e.g. syt-4, suggesting that syt-1 and syt-2 form a hetero-oligomeric complex. Interestingly, stronger immunoblotting signals for syt-2 are detected in the cerebellum in line with observations by others (see Geppert et al 1991 in additional literature).\n\n22/11/2017 Pim\n- Based on the known transmembrane topology of the protein, the \"integral component of ... membrane\" term was chosen.. Experimental description: Materials and Methods:\nSynaptic Vesicle Purification and Immunoisolation-SSV from rat\nbrain cortex were prepared following the method of Huttner et al. (49)\nwith minor variations." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0808-7003" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1542-3498" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3898-5197" ;
        dc:date           "2024-03-14" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_1612" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

